<p>TUR 5/2013 
</p>
<p><b>Turkey  
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p><b>Health;   
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>Allegations concerning a draft health law on &#8220;the organization and duties of the 
</p>
<p>Ministry of Health and its attached units and amendments in some laws&#8221;. According 
</p>
<p>to the information received, the Turkish Parliament is, after initial debates in June 
</p>
<p>2013, considering adoption of this bill, which would criminalize the provision of 
</p>
<p>independent emergency health care by qualified practitioners throughout Turkey and 
</p>
<p>provide the Ministry of Health with unprecedented control over healthcare practices in 
</p>
<p>the country. It is further reported that the bill does not comply with articles 97 and 98 
</p>
<p>of the Turkish Penal Code, which criminalises the refusal by medical personnel of 
</p>
<p>emergency assistance. Further, the bill is reported to include provisions that 
</p>
<p>undermine patient privacy and medical professional ethics. Concern is in particular 
</p>
<p>expressed at the bill&#8217;s alleged negative impact on the ability of health workers to carry 
</p>
<p>out their professional responsibilities without interference or fear of reprisal. 
</p>
<p>30/01/2014 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
</p>
<p> 
