<p><b>expression;  
</b></p>
<p><b>Health;   
</b></p>
<p> 
</p>
<p>Allegations concerning the draft Special Secrets Bill which could seriously restrict the 
</p>
<p>right to freedom of opinion and expression in Japan. According to the information 
</p>
<p>received, the Lower House of the Japanese Parliament was at the time of writing 
</p>
<p>deliberating a bill, approved by the Cabinet in October 2013. The draft Bill reportedly 
</p>
<p>includes a number of provisions that may not be in line with international human rights 
</p>
<p>standards on freedom of opinion and expression and with Japan&#8217;s Constitution, which 
</p>
<p>recognizes the right to access information as part of the right to freedom of expression 
</p>
<p>as a fundamental right. It is alleged that, if enacted, the Bill would provide very broad 
</p>
<p>grounds for secrecy, limited oversight on decisions to classify matters as state secrets, 
</p>
<p>and potential penalization of disclosure of confidential information including by 
</p>
<p>whistleblowers and the press. 
</p>
<p>31/01/2014 
</p>
<p>31/01/2014 
</p>
